Feather mites of the subfamily Xolalginae (Analgoidea: Xolalgidae ) are small-sized xolalgids easily discernible from other feather mites in having a unique feature in males—tibiae and tarsi of legs IV are modified in chelae (
,
). These chela-like structures are used for seizing legs IV of females in the process of copulation and period of precopulatory guarding (
;
;
). In the plumage of avian hosts, these mites as for other xolalgids are located on the down feathers and basal parts of body contour feathers, where the barbules are thread-like and do not form a vane. Mites of the subfamily Xolalginae did not attract much attention of acarologists dealing with feather mites apparently because of their small size (less than 300 micrometers long)

2014;
). Most described mite species live on the flight feathers (remiges and rectrices) and belong to the family Proctophyllodidae :
